-- Sub-Saharan Africa Stocks: Afribank, Oceanic Bank, Wema Bank, Oceanic Move
-- B y   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a
-- 2010-11-02T15:57:24Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-02/sub-saharan-africa-stocks-afribank-oceanic-bank-wema-bank-oceanic-move.html
Kenya’s  All-Share Index  declined 0.7
percent to 84.41 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi.  The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index  dropped the
most since Oct. 21, retreating 1.2 percent to 24,804.22 by the
close in Lagos, according to an e-mailed statement from the
bourse. Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  closed unchanged at
826.46 at 5 p.m. in Windhoek. The  Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share
Index  was little changed at 6,741.91 by the 1 p.m. close in
Accra. Mauritius’s  stock exchange  was closed for a public
holiday.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Oceanic Bank International Plc  (OCEANIC NL), a Nigerian
lender, rose for the 17th day, its longest streak of gains since
at least July 2004, adding 12 kobo, or 5 percent, to 2.54 naira,
the highest since Jan. 14.  The Asset Management Corp. of Nigeria, a government agency
set up to buy bad debts from lenders bailed out by the country’s
central bank last year, start its work as early as next week,
after its directors are approved by the lawmakers,  Tunde Lemo , a
governor of the Central Bank of Nigeria, said yesterday.  Afribank Nigeria Plc  (AFRIBANK NL), increased for a ninth
day, adding 11 kobo, or 4.9 percent, to 2.38 kobo, while  Wema
Bank Plc  (WEMABANK NL) gained 4.9 percent to 1.28 naira, the
highest since Feb. 12.  Bank PHB Plc  (PLATINUM NL) rallied 4.8
percent to 1.54 naira, the highest since July 29.  To contact the reporter on this story:
